1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 a6 8. Ne2 $5
{Quite a rare continuation, whose idea is to build a strong centre with c2-c3.}
(8. Qd2 {is a much more popular line.}) 8... Qb6 {Morozevich plays his
favourite line in this variation, despite his loss to Topalov in Linares last
year.} ({It's interesting to point out that Topalov has played this variation
himself with the black pieces and avoided 8...Qb6 line. I assume that
Predojevic prepared some improvement after 8...Be7.} 8... Be7 9. c3 O-O 10. g3
cxd4 11. Nexd4 Nc5 12. Bg2 Bd7 13. O-O Rc8 14. Kh1 Ne4 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. c4 a5
17. Qc2 g6 18. Rad1 Nc5 19. Nd4 Qc7 20. g4 Rfd8 21. Qf2 Be8 22. f5 Qxe5 23.
fxe6 $2 ({Much better is:} 23. Nf3 $1 {attacking the queen and the knight.} Qd6
24. fxg6 $1 Ne4 (24... hxg6 25. Ng5 Bxg5 26. Bxg5 f5 (26... Rd7 27. Bf6 $18 {
[%cal Yf2h4]}) 27. gxf5 gxf5 28. Rg1 Rd7 (28... Bg6 29. Bxd8 $18 {[%cal Yg2d5]}
) 29. Be3 $18) (24... fxg6 25. Ng5 Bxg5 (25... Nd7 26. Nf7 $18) 26. Bxc5 Bh4
27. Qg1 $1 Qc7 28. Qe3 Bf7 29. Qh6 g5 30. Qf6 {[%cal Yc5d4]} e5 31. Be7 Rf8 32.
cxd5 cxd5 33. Rxd5 $18) 25. gxh7+ Kh8 (25... Kxh7 26. Ng5+ $1 Nxg5 27. Qh4+ Kg8
28. Bxg5 $18) 26. Qc2 $18) 23... Nxe6 24. Nxe6 Qxe6 25. Rde1 Qxg4 26. Bd4 Qh4
$17 {0-1 Cheparinov,I (2696)-Topalov,V (2767)/Sofia BUL 2008/The Week in Chess
705 (38)}) 9. Qc1 g5 {Trying to literally destroy White's centre.} 10. c3 cxd4
11. cxd4 Bb4+ $1 {It is very important to make White's monarch move to the
a7-g1 diagonal.} 12. Kf2 f6 13. g3 {In this opening line White needs to
stabilize the situation, which will promise him a big advantage, thanks to his
strong centre, space advantage and Black's passive light-squared bishop.
However, it turns out that Black has enough dynamic resources to exploit the
vulnerable position of White's king.[%csl Rc8,Yd4,Ye5,Yf4,Yg3]} g4 $1 $146 {
Here is another opening bomb by Alexander! It should be said that this
improvement is clearly showed by Fritz... From now on there follows a series
of forced moves.} ({Morozevich was definitely unhappy with opening results in
his game against Topalov:} 13... Rf8 14. Kg2 g4 15. Nh4 Rg8 (15... fxe5 16.
fxe5 Be7 17. h3 $14) 16. h3 h5 17. hxg4 hxg4 18. Nc3 fxe5 (18... Nxd4 19. exf6
Nxf6 20. Na4 Qa7 21. Qd1 $18) 19. fxe5 Ncxe5 (19... Nxd4 20. Nf5 $1 (20. Na4 $5
Qc6 21. Bxd4 Qxa4 22. Bd3 $44) 20... exf5 21. Nxd5 Qa5 22. Bc4 (22. Nc7+ Kd8
23. Qc4 b5 $13) 22... b5 23. Bb3 Bb7 24. Bxd4 $16) 20. dxe5 d4 21. Na4 Qa5 22.
Qc4 Nxe5 23. Qxd4 Nf3 24. Nxf3 $18 {1-0 Topalov,V (2783)-Morozevich,A (2741)/
Morelia/Linares MEX/ESP 2007/The Week in Chess 642 (48)}) 14. Nh4 (14. Ne1 {is
even worse:[%cal Ye1d3]} fxe5 15. dxe5 (15. fxe5 Rf8+ 16. Kg2 Bxe1 $1 17. Qxe1
Ndxe5 $19) 15... d4 (15... Bc5 16. Nd3) 16. Nxd4 Bxe1+ (16... Nxd4 $2 17. Qc4
Bc5 18. b4 $16) 17. Qxe1 Nxd4 18. Qc3 Qc6 (18... Nb5 $2 19. Qb3 $16) 19. Qxd4
Qxh1 20. Rd1 Qf3+ 21. Kg1 Qd5 $19) 14... fxe5 {Blowing up White's centre.} 15.
fxe5 (15. dxe5 $2 {loses immediately:} Bc5 $1 {[%cal Yd5d4]} (15... d4 {
doesn't work, in view of} 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Qc4 $16) 16. Bxc5 Nxc5 $19 {[%cal
Rc5d3]}) 15... Ndxe5 $1 {This is the point! The diagonal a7-g1 is opening for
Black's queen!} (15... O-O+ {would be a huge mistake.} 16. Kg2 $16) 16. dxe5 d4
17. Bf4 Rf8 $1 {White's pieces are located so awkwardly that Black has enough
time to activate all his forces.} 18. Kg2 Bd7 $1 {The bishop is ready to
occupy the long diagonal.} 19. h3 {White tries to eliminate the g4 pawn, which
will give White's monarch the h3 shelter. This move looks like the least of
the evils. I haven't found anything better:} (19. a3 Be7 20. b4 d3 {[%cal
Yb6f2]} 21. Be3 Qb5 {[%cal Yb5d5]} 22. Nc3 Qc4 $17) (19. Qc2 Nxe5 {[%cal Rd7c6]
} 20. Bxe5 Bc6+ 21. Kg1 d3+ 22. Bd4 Qxd4+ 23. Nxd4 dxc2 {[%cal Yb4c5]} 24. Nxe6
Rf6 $19) 19... d3 20. hxg4 {Again the best.} (20. Be3 Qa5 21. Nf4 Nxe5 22. Kh2
Rc8 23. Qd1 Rc2+ 24. Bg2 Rxf4 $1 25. Bxf4 Nf3+ 26. Nxf3 gxf3 27. Rg1 Qd5 $17) (
20. Nc3 Nxe5 21. Qe3 Bc6+ 22. Kh2 Qxe3 23. Bxe3 Bxh1 (23... Nc4 24. Bh6 Rf2+)
24. Kxh1 Rd8 $19) 20... dxe2 21. Bxe2 Nd4 $15 {Black has won the material back,
and, thanks to better located pieces and a slightly safer king, his advantage
changes from slight to obvious.} 22. Qe3 $2 {It was not a good idea to put the
queen on the diagonal, where the dark-squared bishop is going to operate...} ({
Somehow after} 22. Bf3 $1 {Fritz doesn't show a clear way to get a big
advantage:} Rc8 $1 (22... Nxf3 $2 23. Nxf3 Bc6 24. Rh6 $1 O-O-O (24... Rc8 25.
Qd1 $13) 25. Rxe6 Kb8 $2 26. Rxc6 $16) 23. Qd1 Rc2+ (23... Be7 24. Kh3 Nxf3 25.
Nxf3 Qxb2 26. Rb1 Qc2 $15) 24. Kh3 Rxb2 $15) 22... Bc5 $17 {Strong and simple.
Now White is in trouble.} 23. b4 (23. Kh3 Nc2 24. Qd2 Nxa1 25. Rxa1 O-O-O 26.
Bg5 (26. Rc1 Bc6 27. Qc2 Be3 28. Bxe3 Qxe3 29. Bxa6 Kb8 $19) 26... Rde8 27. Bf6
Rf7 28. g5 Bc6 29. Bh5 Rd7 $17) 23... Qxb4 24. Rhb1 $6 {White has tried to
move away the kingside rook from the h1-a8 diagonal, but his other rook is now
stuck in the corner.} ({Better was} 24. Rab1 Bc6+ (24... Qa5 25. Kh3 Bc6 26.
Rhc1 $15) 25. Kh3 Nxe2 26. Qxe2 Qe4 $17) 24... Qa5 25. Kh3 (25. Rd1 {doesn't
change too much:} O-O-O 26. Rac1 Ba4 $1 27. Rxd4 Rxd4 28. Qc3 (28. Qxd4 Bc6+)
28... Qxc3 29. Rxc3 Bc6+ $19) 25... Nxe2 26. Qxe2 Bd4 $19 {Winning an exchange.
Black gets a big material advantage, while White has no compensation.} 27. Bh6
(27. Qe4 Bxa1 28. Rxa1 Bc6 (28... O-O-O 29. Bg5 Rde8 30. Bf6 $17) 29. Qxh7
O-O-O $19) 27... Rf2 28. Qe4 Bxa1 29. Rxa1 O-O-O {The rest is a matter of
simple technique.} 30. Bg5 Bc6 31. Rc1 Qd5 32. Qxh7 Qxa2 33. Rxc6+ bxc6 34. Nf3
Rxf3 35. Bxd8 Kxd8 {and Black easily escapes from checks. A very important
game for the theory of 8.Ne2 line. White will have to come up with some new
idea, otherwise, they will have to switch back to 8.Qd2.} 0-1

