1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ {The idea of this rare
continuation is to prevent the development of White's queenside knight to c3.
More popular lines are:} (4... Nf6) (4... Bc5) 5. c3 (5. Nc3 {would probably
lead to the Four Knights Opening:} Nf6) 5... Bc5 6. Nxc6 bxc6 ({Of course} 6...
Qf6 $4 {is not possible anymore, because of} 7. Nd4) 7. Bd3 Ne7 {Completing
the development. Usually Black transfers his knight to e5 via g6.} ({In the
most populat game of this line Black has tried to activate the queen first,
and only then to complete the development of the kingside:} 7... Qh4 8. Qe2 Nf6
9. h3 $1 {However, Kasparov managed to exploit the unfortunate position of
Black's queen:} O-O 10. g3 Qh5 11. g4 Qe5 12. g5 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Re8 14. Bf3
Qxe2+ 15. Bxe2 Ba6 16. c4 Bxc4 17. Nc3 $16 {1-0 Kasparov,G-Leko,P/Fontys 1997/
CBM 61 (31)}) 8. O-O {Morozevich chooses the most natural move keeping all the
available plans open. White played the more aggressive 8.Qh5 and 8.h4, as well
as more popular 8.Nd2 in the preceeding games:} (8. Nd2 O-O ({Black hasn't
equalized after} 8... d5 9. O-O O-O 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. c4 $1 {The threat c4-c5
forces Black into the following simplification.} dxe4 12. Bxe4 Qxd1 13. Rxd1
Be6 14. Bd3 $14 {1/2-1/2 Bacrot,E (2645)-Fontaine,R (2541)/Aix les Bains 2003 
(59)}) 9. O-O d6 10. Kh1 (10. b4 {could be recommended.} Bb6 11. a4 {and there
is no clear way to equalize the game. For instance:} a5 12. Nc4 Be6 13. Nxb6
cxb6 14. Be3) 10... f5 11. f4 Bb6 12. Qf3 Kh8 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Bxf5 Nxf5 $11 {
0-1 Wiersma,E (2414)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2672)/Fuegen 2006/CBM 115 (38)}) (8. h4 $5
{The idea of this early pawn advance is to attack Black's monarch's residence.
[%cal Yh4h5,Yh5h6]} O-O (8... d5 {looks more logical.}) 9. h5 h6 ({Probably
better was} 9... f5 $5 10. e5 d6 11. h6 g6 12. Bc4+ $1 d5 (12... Kh8 13. b4 Bb6
14. Bg5 $1 Qe8 15. Bf6+ $14) 13. Bd3 $14) 10. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 11. Qg4+ Kh8 (11...
Kh7 $2 12. e5+ Kh8 13. Qf4 f5 (13... Kg7 $2 14. Qf6+ Kg8 15. Qxh6 f5 16. exf6
$18) (13... Ng8 $2 14. Qf5 $18) 14. Qxh6+ Kg8 15. g4 $1 $40) 12. Qf4 $14 {1/
2-1/2 Nataf,I (2526)-Miles,A (2584)/Mondariz 2000 (60)[%csl Rc5,Rh6,Rh8][%cal
Gf4e5]}) ({White hasn't got anything special after} 8. Qh5 d6 9. Bg5 Rb8 10. b3
O-O 11. Nd2 Qe8 12. b4 Bb6 13. Nc4 Ng6 14. Nxb6 axb6 15. Be3 f5 $1 $11 {1/2-1/
2 Sax,G (2570)-Miles,A (2595)/Szeged 1997}) 8... O-O 9. Bg5 $5 $146 {
Morozevich's abilitiy to find new moves and ideas is incredible! This moves
looks so logical: it prevents normal development of black's kingside and makes
him weaken its position. Every time I encounter one of Morozevich's novelties,
I ask myself: "How come that nobody played it before?!"} (9. Nd2 {was mainly
played previously, which leads to 8.Nd2 0-0 9.0-0 line.}) ({Another possible
attempt to fight for an opening advantage is} 9. b4 Bb6 10. a4 a5 11. Nd2 d5
12. exd5 $6 {improving Black's pawn structure.} (12. Nb3 {looks better:} dxe4 (
12... Re8 13. Qc2 $14) 13. Bxe4 Bf5 14. Bxf5 Nxf5 15. Bf4 $14) 12... cxd5 $2 ({
Much stronger was} 12... axb4 $1 13. cxb4 Nxd5 $15 14. Ba3 $2 Ne3 $1 $19) 13.
Nb3 c6 (13... Nc6 $5 14. b5 Ne5 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Qh5+ Kg8 17. Qxe5 $14) 14.
Ba3 axb4 15. Bxb4 Re8 16. Qc2 Ng6 17. a5 Ba7 18. Rfe1 $14 {0-1 Drei,A (2351)
-Miles,A (2579)/Reykjavik 2000/CBM 075 ext (29)}) 9... f6 10. Bh4 d6 $6 {
Somehow after this move I wasn't able to find a way to equalize the game for
Black...} ({More consistent and stronger was} 10... Ng6 $1 {activating the
knight} 11. Bg3 Ne5 12. Be2 (12. b4 Bb6 13. Na3 d5) (12. Kh1 {[%cal Yf2f4]} d5
$1 $15) 12... d5 $11 {and Black's active pieces compensate for his inferior
pawn structure.}) 11. Nd2 Ng6 12. Bg3 f5 {It looks like with this breakthrough
Black solves all the opening problems, but it is not the case. White has
always a slight advantage due to a superior pawn structure.} (12... Ne5 {
doesn't solve all the problems:} 13. Nb3 Bb6 14. Nd4 Bd7 (14... Nxd3 15. Qxd3
c5 (15... Bd7 16. Nxc6 {[%cal Yd3c4]}) 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17. exf5 d5 18. Rfe1 $16)
15. Be2 $14 {with following a2-a4.}) 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Bxf5 Rxf5 15. a4 {
Threatening to kill the bishop with b2-b4.} a6 (15... a5 {perhaps was better
than the move in the text, but White would have kept the initiative either way:
} 16. Qb3+ (16. b4 Bb6) 16... Kh8 17. Rae1 Rb8 18. Qc2 Qd7 19. Nc4 $14) 16.
Qb3+ $1 {With the brilliant transfer of the queen to b7, where it looks to be
awkward, Morozevich gets an obvious advantage. It is not so easy for Black to
protect all his queenside pawns.} Kh8 17. Qb7 $1 Rb8 $2 {This logical move is
actually bad. After White gets a passed a-pawn, it turns out that Black cannot
do anything with his virtually active pieces.} (17... Rd5 {is Fritz's
suggestion. Black blocks the main diagonal, forcing White to trade the queens:}
18. Ne4 Qc8 19. Qxc8+ (19. Qxc6 Ne7 $19) 19... Rxc8 20. Rfe1 $14) (17... Ne7 {
looks passive, but White's advantage is not as big as in the game:} 18. Ne4 (
18. Bh4 g5) 18... Qb8 (18... Bb6 19. Bh4 Qc8 20. Qxc8+ Nxc8 $16) (18... h6 19.
Rad1 Qb8 20. Qxb8+ Rxb8 21. Rfe1 $14 Ng6 $2 22. Nxc5 Rxc5 23. Rxd6 $16) 19.
Qxb8+ Rxb8 20. Rfe1 $14) 18. Qxa6 Rxb2 19. Ne4 $16 {White easily neutralizes
Black's initiative and converts his positional advantage to convincing victory.
} h5 (19... h6 20. a5 $16 (20. Qxc6 Rb6)) 20. h4 $1 {The key move. After Black
is stopped on the kingside and White got another important spot g5, it looks
like Black's position became lost...} Rb6 ({Of course Black cannot take the
pawn:} 20... Nxh4 $4 21. Bxh4 Qxh4 22. Qc8+ $18) (20... Nf4 {was another
logical attempt to attack White's king. But, White's position is solid enough
to parry all the threats:} 21. Rfe1 (21. Qxc6 $4 Rb6) 21... Qf8 22. Qxc6 $1 ({
Only not} 22. Kh2 $2 Nxg2 23. Kxg2 Rfxf2+ 24. Nxf2 Rxf2+ 25. Bxf2 Qxf2+ 26. Kh3
Qf3+ 27. Kh2 $11) 22... Ne2+ (22... Nxg2 23. Kxg2 Bxf2 24. Nxf2 Rfxf2+ 25. Kh1
$18) 23. Kh2 Nxg3 24. fxg3 $18) ({In event of} 20... Qf8 {White plays cool,
taking the pawn:} 21. Qxc6 Ne5 22. Bxe5 Rxe5 23. a5 $18 {and there is nothing
Black can do.}) 21. Qc4 Qg8 (21... Qf8 {is met by} 22. Qe2 {[%cal Ye4g5]}) (
21... Rb2 22. Qe6 $1 Ne7 23. Rae1 $18) 22. Qe2 Rb8 $2 {loses right away.} ({
The last chance was} 22... Qe6 23. Rfe1 $18) 23. Ng5 $18 {Now the game is over,
since White wins the h5 pawn and develops a decisive attack.} Nf8 24. Qxh5+ Nh7
25. Rae1 Bb6 26. Re7 Rbf8 27. Kh2 R5f6 28. a5 {Another impressive victory by
the Winner of Sarajevo!} 1-0

